<div id="review_739189101" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/739189101" />
    <a title="Robb Bridson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10357507-robb-bridson"><img alt="Robb Bridson" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/739189101?book_show_action=true">Oct 11, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Robb Bridson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Robb Bridson" href="/user/show/10357507-robb-bridson">Robb Bridson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audio CD 9781452658582" href="/book/show/15812635-the-party-is-over">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer739189101" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5773710658862499848">More entertaining than informative, but that&apos;s kind of what I was expecting. I&apos;d read articles and interviews, and enjoyed Lofgren&apos;s blunt, witty, and angry style. The audiobook reader, at first funny but eventually tedious, added quite a bit of crotchety old man to the delivery.<br/><br/>The basic point of the book is exactly the title. Lofgren is an ex-insider with great contempt toward the insane GOP he worked for, the weak and hypocritical Democrats who fail to act as a counterforce, and the entire Wa</span>
  <span id="freeText5773710658862499848" style="display:none">More entertaining than informative, but that's kind of what I was expecting. I'd read articles and interviews, and enjoyed Lofgren's blunt, witty, and angry style. The audiobook reader, at first funny but eventually tedious, added quite a bit of crotchety old man to the delivery.<br /><br />The basic point of the book is exactly the title. Lofgren is an ex-insider with great contempt toward the insane GOP he worked for, the weak and hypocritical Democrats who fail to act as a counterforce, and the entire Washington culture. As most sane non-insiders do.<br /><br />Unfortunately, while I agree with his assessment (though some of his details are a bit off) and am sympathetic to the solutions he gives, I think a lot is missed. While he accurately notes our government's systemic problems, he seems to think it's all about corporate money. He fails to recognize the other systemic issues that if we leave in tact, no campaign finance will fix.<br />He seems to focus more on individuals than on larger cultural issues or some of the more complex incentive issues (beyond money).<br /><br />So all in all, while it's a refreshing vent, the book doesn't offer much insight or direction. It just tells us what we know (and if we don't know it, he won't persuade us).</span>
  <a data-text-id="5773710658862499848" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


